<li><cite id="CITEREFWallace1992" class="citation book cs1">Wallace, Robert K. (1992). <i>Melville &amp; Turner: Spheres of Love and Fright</i>. The University of Georgia Press. <a href="/wiki/ISBN_(identifier)" class="mw-redirect" title="ISBN (identifier)">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/0-8203-1366-1" title="Special:BookSources/0-8203-1366-1"><bdi>0-8203-1366-1</bdi></a>.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Melville+%26+Turner%3A+Spheres+of+Love+and+Fright&amp;rft.pub=The+University+of+Georgia+Press&amp;rft.date=1992&amp;rft.isbn=0-8203-1366-1&amp;rft.aulast=Wallace&amp;rft.aufirst=Robert+K.&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AHerman+Melville" class="Z3988"></span> "Wallace explores the stylistic and aesthetic affinities of English landscape painter <a href="/wiki/J._M._W._Turner" title="J. M. W. Turner">J. M. W. Turner</a> (1775-1851) and American novelist Herman Melville, establishing Turner as a decisive influence on the creation of Melville's <i>Moby-Dick</i>". (Quotation from dust jacket)</li></ul>
